FAA flight data exploration¶

by Gary Cheng¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset containing airlines, airports, minutes of arrival/departure delays, reasons for delays, and some other flight related attributes for approximately 7 million scheduled domestic flights within the United States in 2008.

# Merge airports and carrier dataframes and include the actual names for airports in new columns 

df_08 = pd.merge(df_08, airports[['iata','airport']], how='left',left_on='Origin', right_on='iata')
df_08 = pd.merge(df_08, airports[['iata','airport']], how='left',left_on='Dest', right_on='iata')

# Merge airport dataframe to get the state where the airport is located in, and put into new columns
df_08 = pd.merge(df_08, airports[['iata','state']], how='left', left_on='Origin', right_on='iata')
df_08 = pd.merge(df_08, airports[['iata','state']], how='left', left_on='Dest', right_on='iata')

# Merge airports and carrier dataframes and include the actual names of unique carriers in new column
df_08 = pd.merge(df_08, carriers, how='left',left_on='UniqueCarrier', right_on='Code')

# Rename newly added columns to appropriate names
df_08.rename(columns={"airport_x": "airport_origin", "airport_y": "airport_dest",
                      "Description":"Airline", 'state_x':'origin_state', 'state_y':'dest_state'}, inplace=True)

# Drop columns that will not be used in the analysis
df_08.drop(columns=['iata_x','iata_y','Code','FlightNum','TailNum','ActualElapsedTime',
                    'CRSElapsedTime','AirTime'],inplace=True)

# Function to the hour from time columns having 24-hour format hhmm
def get_hour(data):
    if len(data) == 4:
        #hour = data[:2]
        return data[:2]
    elif len(data) == 3:
        #hour = data[:1]
        return data[:1]
    else:
        #hour = 0
        return 0
    #return hour

# Function to get cancellation reason from cancellation code
def cancel_reason(code):
    if code=='A':
        return 'Carrier'
    elif code=='B':
        return 'Weather'
    elif code=='C':
        return 'NAS'
    elif code=='D':
        return 'Security'

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are about 7 millions flights in this dataset from 2008, with 29 columns in total. Out of which 18 are numerical and 11 are categorical variables. Numerical variables include arrival/departure delay, elapsed time, taxi in/out times, and delay minutes in various delay category buckets. Categorical variables include year, month, day of month, day of week, unique, origin airport, destination airport, carrier (airline), cancelled (yes/no), diverted (yes/no), and cancellation code. Out of the categorical variables, the date relates ones are ordinal in nature.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in figuring out the effects different variables have on delayed, cancelled, and diverted flights across the US.

  • Arrival delay, in minutes
  • Departure delay, in minutes
  • Scheduled arrival/departure times
  • Type of delay
  • Whether flight is delayed or cancelled

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect the following variables will be a factor in determining flight performance. For example, there would be more delays and cancellations during the winter months compared to spring and fall, and that delays happen more often during the busier hours of the day.

  • Day of week
  • Month
  • Day of month
  • Scheduled arrival and departure times
  • Unique carrier (airline)
  • Origin/Destination airports
  • Distance between origin and destination

Univariate Exploration¶

Start looking at distribution of array delay minutes.

Investigate Arrival Delay in minutes¶

The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) considers a flight to be delayed when it is 15 minutes later than its scheduled time. All delay values are shown in the dataset including ones between 0 and 15 minutes. A negative value means that the flight has arrived or departed earlier than its scheduled time.

Below we can see that the cause of delay time columns (Carrier, Weather, NAS, Security, Late Aircraft) is not populated for arrival delays that are less than 15 minutes.

Overall Percentages of Delayed Flights¶

FAA considers a flight to be delayed when it is 15 minutes later than its scheduled time. 22.2% and 19.3% of flights experience delays of 15 minutes or more, for arriving and departing flights, respectively.

Also more columns were added for the airport and airline names, and DepDate to show the departing date in YYYY-mm-dd format.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

In terms of cancellation reason, I expected a majority of cancellations to be from weather. However, it looks like the airlines cancel flights at roughly the same number as ones due to weather.

def plot_delay_type(by,busy_airports=False,n=10):
    
    if busy_airports:
        top_n = df_08['airport_dest'].value_counts().iloc[:n].index.tolist()
        busiest_airports = df_08[df_08['airport_dest'].isin(top_n)]
        df_plot = busiest_airports.groupby(by)[['CarrierDelay','WeatherDelay','NASDelay',
                          'SecurityDelay','LateAircraftDelay']].mean().reset_index().set_index(by)
    else:
        # Create df_plot for plotting purposes
        df_plot = df_08.groupby(by)[['CarrierDelay','WeatherDelay','NASDelay',
                          'SecurityDelay','LateAircraftDelay']].mean().reset_index().set_index(by)
    
    # Create new column adding up all cancellation summary values
    df_plot['temp'] = df_plot['CarrierDelay'] + df_plot['WeatherDelay'] + df_plot['NASDelay'] + df_plot['SecurityDelay'] + df_plot['LateAircraftDelay']

    # Sort by descending total number of cancellations in TotalCancel column
    df_plot = df_plot.sort_values(by = 'temp', ascending=False).head(n)

    # Drop the TotalCancel column so it won't be plotted 
    df_plot.drop(columns = 'temp',inplace=True)
    
    # Reverse the dataframe so that the horizontal plot will plot the maximum from top instead of bottom
    df_plot = df_plot.iloc[::-1]
    
    #N = 5
    CDelay = df_plot['CarrierDelay']
    WDelay = df_plot['WeatherDelay']
    NDelay = df_plot['NASDelay']
    SDelay = df_plot['SecurityDelay']
    LDelay = df_plot['LateAircraftDelay']
    
    ind = np.arange(n)    # the x locations for the groups
    width = 0.5       # the width of the bars: can also be len(x) sequence
    
    sb.set(style='whitegrid', font_scale=1.2)
    plt.figure(figsize = [10, 7])
    p1 = plt.barh(ind, CDelay, width, color='#003f5c')
    p2 = plt.barh(ind, WDelay, width, left=CDelay, color='#58508d')
    p3 = plt.barh(ind, NDelay, width, left=WDelay+CDelay, color='#bc5090')
    p4 = plt.barh(ind, SDelay, width, left=WDelay+CDelay+NDelay, color='#ff6361')
    p5 = plt.barh(ind, LDelay, width, left=WDelay+CDelay+NDelay+SDelay, color='#ffa600')

    plt.xlabel('Minutes')
    plt.title('Average Arrival Delay in Minutes with Delay Type')
    plt.yticks(ind, df_plot.index)
    plt.xticks(np.arange(0, 70, 10))
    plt.legend((p1[0], p2[0], p3[0], p4[0], p5[0]), df_plot.columns, loc='lower right')

    plt.show()

# Helper function to generate cancellation code plots

def plot_cancel_v(by,n=10,sorted=True, order='top'):     # count default is 10
    # Create df_plot for plotting purposes
    df_plot = df_08.groupby(['CancellationCode', by]).size().reset_index().pivot(columns='CancellationCode',
                                                                                   index=by, values=0)
    # Fill NaN with zeros
    df_plot.fillna(0, inplace = True)

    # Create new column adding up all cancellation summary values
    df_plot['TotalCancel'] = df_plot['Carrier'] + df_plot['NAS'] + df_plot['Security'] + df_plot['Weather']
    
    if sorted and order=='top':
        # Sort by descending total number of cancellations in TotalCancel column
        df_plot = df_plot.sort_values(by = 'TotalCancel',ascending=False).head(n)
    elif sorted and order=='bottom':
        # Sort by ascending total number of cancellations in TotalCancel column
        df_plot = df_plot.sort_values(by = 'TotalCancel',ascending=True).head(n)
    else:
        # Values are not sorted, useful for ordinal variables
        df_plot = df_plot.head(n)
        
    # Drop the TotalCancel column so it won't be plotted 
    df_plot.drop(columns = 'TotalCancel',inplace=True)
    
    # Generate plot
    df_plot.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True);

    df_plot['TotalCancel'] = df_plot['Carrier'] + df_plot['NAS'] + df_plot['Security'] + df_plot['Weather']
    
    if sorted and order=='top':
        # Sort by descending total number of cancellations in TotalCancel column
        df_plot = df_plot.sort_values(by = 'TotalCancel',ascending=False).head(n)
    elif sorted and order=='bottom':
        # Sort by ascending total number of cancellations in TotalCancel column
        df_plot = df_plot.sort_values(by = 'TotalCancel',ascending=True).head(n)
    else:
        # Values are not sorted, useful for ordinal variables
        df_plot = df_plot.head(n)
    
    if orientation == 'h':
        # Get maximum value for x axis number so that the axis is labelled with proper range
        x_max = (df_plot['TotalCancel'].iloc[0])
    
        # Drop the TotalCancel column so it won't be plotted 
        df_plot.drop(columns = 'TotalCancel',inplace=True)
    
        # Reverse the dataframe so that the horizontal plot will plot the maximum from top instead of bottom
        df_plot = df_plot.iloc[::-1]
    
        # Generate plot
    
        Carrier = df_plot['Carrier']
        NAS = df_plot['NAS']
        Security = df_plot['Security']
        Weather = df_plot['Weather']
    
        ind = np.arange(n)    # the x locations for the groups
        width = 0.5       # the width of the bars: can also be len(x) sequence
    
        sb.set(style='whitegrid', font_scale=1.2)
        plt.figure(figsize = [10, 7])
        p1 = plt.barh(ind, Carrier, width, color='#004c6d')

        p3 = plt.barh(ind, Security, width, left=Carrier+NAS, color='#8eb8d3')

        plt.xlabel('Count')
        plt.title('Number of Flight Cancellations')
        
        if by == 'Month':

            plt.yticks(ind, ylabels)

            ylabels.reverse()

            plt.yticks(ind, df_plot.index)

        plt.legend((p1[0], p2[0], p3[0], p4[0]), df_plot.columns, loc='best', title='Cancellation Code')

# Helper function to generation cancellation and diversion rates plots

def plot_rates(by,n=10,order='top'):  # make default count 10 and descending order
    
    if order == 'top':
        asc = False
    elif order == 'bottom':
        asc = True
    
    cancel = df_08.groupby(by).Cancelled.sum().reset_index()
    divert = df_08.groupby(by).Diverted.sum().reset_index()
    cancel['Diverted'] = divert['Diverted']
    total_flights = df_08.groupby(by).Month.count().reset_index()
    
    cancel = pd.merge(cancel, total_flights[[by,'Month']], 
                              how='left', left_on=by, right_on=by)
    cancel.rename(columns={'Month': 'TotalFlights'}, inplace=True)
    cancel['cancel_rate'] =  cancel.Cancelled / cancel.TotalFlights
    cancel['divert_rate'] =  cancel.Diverted / cancel.TotalFlights
    
    cancel_summary = cancel.groupby(by).cancel_rate.mean().reset_index()
    cancel_summary.nlargest(10,columns='cancel_rate')
    divert_summary = cancel.groupby(by).divert_rate.mean().reset_index()
    divert_summary.nlargest(10,columns='divert_rate')
    
    # create main plot with subplots
    plt.figure(figsize = [8, 8])
    # subplot 1: cancelled
    plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
    sb.barplot(x=cancel_summary.groupby(by).cancel_rate.mean().sort_values(ascending=asc).head(n)
           , y=cancel_summary.groupby(by).cancel_rate.mean().sort_values(ascending=asc).head(n).index, color='steelblue');
    
    # subplot 2: diverted
    plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
    sb.barplot(x=divert_summary.groupby(by).divert_rate.mean().sort_values(ascending=asc).head(n)
           , y=divert_summary.groupby(by).divert_rate.mean().sort_values(ascending=asc).head(n).index, color='steelblue');
    
    plt.show()

# Helper function for multivariate plot

def multivplot(cat_var, sample=True, size=500):
    
    if sample:
        samples = np.random.choice(df_08.shape[0], size, replace = False)
        df_08_sam = df_08.loc[samples,:]
        outliers = (((df_08_sam.DepDelay - df_08_sam.DepDelay.mean()).abs() > df_08_sam.DepDelay.std()*3) | 
            ((df_08_sam.ArrDelay - df_08_sam.ArrDelay.mean()).abs() > df_08_sam.ArrDelay.std()*3))
        sb.lmplot('DepDelay', 'ArrDelay', data=df_08_sam[~outliers],
           fit_reg=False, hue=cat_var, scatter_kws={'alpha':0.1})
        plt.show()  
    else:
        outliers = (((df_08.DepDelay - df_08.DepDelay.mean()).abs() > df_08.DepDelay.std()*3) | 
            ((df_08.ArrDelay - df_08.ArrDelay.mean()).abs() > df_08.ArrDelay.std()*3))
        sb.lmplot('DepDelay', 'ArrDelay', data=df_08[~outliers],
           fit_reg=False, hue=cat_var, scatter_kws={'alpha':0.1})
        plt.show()
